he Novel -- t17 Mired in Print: Romantic Writers and Caricature -- t18 ‘A Point to Aim at in a Morning’s Walk’: Encounters at the Print Shop -- t19 Illustrated Poetry in the Romantic Period -- t20 Fashioning the Female Artist: Allegory and Celebrity in Lady Diana Beauclerk’s Watercolours of The Faerie Queene -- t21 Angelica Kauffman and the Sister Arts -- t22 Illustrated Magazines and Periodicals: Visual Genres and Gendered Aspirations -- tPart IV Romanticism Reimagined, the 1830s and Beyond -- t23 Album Culture: Begging for Scraps -- t24 Nineteenth-Century Illustrated Poetry: Mise-en-Page and the Visual Rhythms of Seriality -- t25 Romantic Caricatures and Comics -- t26 Cultural Manifestations of Romanticism on the Contemporary Screen -- t27 Looking Back Through Fashion: Regency Romances and a ‘Jumble of Styles’ -- tNotes on Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe only volume to comprehensively bring together developments from different disciplines that address the complex interplay between British Romantic literature and the visual artsIt covers a wide range of intermedial cultural productions, from popular to elite, and from the public to the domestic sphere, including literary texts, paintings and prints, literary galleries, exhibition catalogues, illustrated magazines, household objects and designAll the essays in this volume are newly commissioned and include cutting edge research from an interdisciplinary group of writers, literary scholars, art historians, and exhibition curatorsIt brings together work of emerging as well as established scholars in the field, from Europe, North America and Australia, reflecting the global significance of this growing fieldFrom the birth of the museum to the explosion of mass-produced illustrated books, the Romantic period (c. 1770-1840) was a moment of rapid change and fruitful experimentation in the fields of art and literature alike. New advances in print production encouraged a wider range of readers to engage with literary forms that opened a path into the once aristocratic field of the visual arts. This Companion captures the way recent engagements with visual studies have reshaped how we approach and understand the boundaries between print and visual culture in the period. It brings together 27 research-led chapters that offer a detailed account of the productive, if sometimes tense, interactions between emergent forms of intermedial expression that were redefining culture in the Romantic period -- as they continue to do today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 03. Jan 2023) 0aRomanticism. 4aLiterary Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh1 aAvery-Quash, Susanna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBatchelor, Jennie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoehm, Katharina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoyce, Charlotte, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrylowe, Thora, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChapman, Alison, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aConstantine, Mary-Ann, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCoutu, Joan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavidson, Hilary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEngel, Laura, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFunnell, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGarner, Katie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrande, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.lo